## Local prerequisites
* Docker (for Postgres). Start DB: `docker compose up -d` from repo root.
* Node + **pnpm** only for JS dependencies: `pnpm install` from repo root.
* **Canonical runbook:** full clone-to-run steps, env vars, ports, and scripts live in the root **[README.md](README.md)**. Prefer updating that file when setup changes.

## README & runbook (must do)
* Whenever you add or change **one-time setup** (migrations, `docker compose` steps, `pnpm workflow:*`, etc.), **new or renamed environment variables**, **new root/workspace scripts**, or **non-obvious local config**, update **[README.md](README.md)** in the **same change** (or immediately after) so the project can always be initialized and run from that file alone.
* Keep **`packages/backend/.env.example`** (and any future package-level `.env.example` files) aligned with required variables; reflect new keys in README when they matter for running the app.

## SQL quick reference (Postgres)
* Clear rows: `DELETE FROM sessions;` (no `*` after `DELETE`). Truncate: `TRUNCATE sessions;`

## Core Architectural Rules & Constraints
* **NO Vercel-hosted infrastructure:** Do not rely on Vercel-managed services (e.g., Vercel KV, Vercel Functions, **Vercel Workflows cloud runtime**). The prototype runs **locally** and uses **self-hosted** Workflow DevKit with **`@workflow/world-postgres`** — not the Vercel “world” for serverless.
* **Durable execution:** Implement durable workflow runs via Workflow DevKit + Postgres world (queue + persistence). **Do not** execute generated workflow user code synchronously on the HTTP request thread; keep long-running work in the workflow runtime after it is wired up.
* **Sandboxed Execution:** AI-generated code must NEVER have direct access to the Node.js host environment, file system, or raw network. It must strictly run inside `rivet-dev/sandbox-agent` and only communicate with the host via explicitly injected, typed functions (the SDK).
* **Mock App Constraints:** Keep the customer support domain "stupid simple." A session only needs an ID, customer name, status ('open' or 'closed'), and sentiment ('happy', 'neutral', 'angry'). Do not build real AI sentiment analysis; rely on manual UI inputs to mock the sentiment for now.

## Git commits (Conventional Commits)

This repo is **fullstack**: most work spans UI, API, and schema. Commits should reflect **what changed for the product or task**, not which package folder you touched.

**Format:** `type(optional-scope): imperative summary` (see [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/)).

**Types:** `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `chore`, `refactor`, `test`, etc.—use what fits.

**Scopes — do this**

* Name the **feature, capability, or ticket**, e.g. `feat(inbox): add session list polling`, `fix(sessions): reject messages on closed session`, `feat(workflows): scaffold builder route`.
* Omit the scope when it is obvious or the change is repo-wide: `chore: update pnpm lockfile`.
* Use a **ticket id** as scope when your team tracks that way: `feat(ACME-42): close session sentiment modal`.

**Scopes — avoid as the default pattern**

* Do **not** use stack-layer scopes such as `feat(backend)` or `feat(frontend)` for product work. A single user-facing change often belongs in **one commit** that updates API, UI, and SQL together; splitting by layer creates noisy history and mismatches how tickets are delivered.

Layer-style scopes are only reasonable for **purely local** changes, e.g. bumping a devDependency that only affects one package, or a mechanical rename inside one app with no behavioral coupling—still prefer a concrete scope (`chore(vite): bump to 6.x`) over a vague `frontend` when you can.

**Subject line:** present tense, imperative, ~72 characters, no trailing period.

## Coding Standards
* **Language:** Strict TypeScript for both frontend and backend.
* **Linting:** After any substantive code change (new or edited TS/TSX), run `pnpm lint` from the repo root and fix reported issues before considering the work complete. Prefer fixing the code over disabling rules unless the rule is a false positive or clearly incompatible with the intended pattern.
* **Package Management:** Strictly use `pnpm`. Do not suggest `npm` or `yarn` commands.
* **Styling:** Use Tailwind CSS for all frontend components. Keep the UI clean but minimal—focus on functionality over complex design.
* **Code Generation:** When generating code for the AI prompt builder, ensure the output is deterministic. Emphasize returning structured JSON containing the trigger event and the raw JS code string.

## Database Schema Reference (Core)
* `sessions`: `id` (UUID, default `uuid_generate_v4()`), `customer_name`, `status` (default `'open'`), `sentiment` (nullable; set on close), `created_at`, `updated_at` (timestamptz)
* `workflows`: `id` (UUID), `name`, `trigger_events` (TEXT[], default `'{}'`), `original_prompt`, `generated_code`, `is_active` (default true), `created_at`, `updated_at` (timestamptz)
* `session_messages`: `id` (UUID), `session_id` (FK → `sessions`), `author_role` (`customer` \| `agent`), `body`, `created_at` (timestamptz)
* **Workflow DevKit (Postgres world):** additional tables/schemas created by `pnpm workflow:postgres-setup` (not in Docker `init/` SQL); includes **graphile-worker** schema for jobs